statement.p:
Factor out the largest perfect square.

108a^5b^2

\dfrac{a^2+4a^4}{8}

Factor out the largest perfect square.

\dfrac{5k^5}{9n} 

32a^{10}-48a^9

Decide whether each statement is true or false.  Then use a calculator to verify your answer.


\sqrt{6} = \sqrt{2}~\sqrt{3}

\sqrt{6} = \sqrt{2}+\sqrt{4}

Find and correct the error in each calculation.

\sqrt{36+64} \rightarrow 6+8

\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{3} \rightarrow \sqrt{6}

Decide whether each statement is true or false. Then use a calculator to verify your answer.

\sqrt{16} = \sqrt{18} - \sqrt{2}

\sqrt{8} = \dfrac{\sqrt{72}}{\sqrt{9}}

\sqrt{5} + \sqrt{5} = \sqrt{10}

\sqrt{2}~\sqrt{9} = \sqrt{18}

solution.p:
The largest perfect square that divides evenly into 45 is 9, so we factor 45 as 9 \cdot 5. We use the product rule to write
	\sqrt{45} = \sqrt{9 \cdot 5} = \sqrt{9}~\sqrt{5}
Finally, we simplify  to get
	\sqrt{45} = \sqrt{9}~\sqrt{5} = 3\sqrt{5}

The largest perfect square that divides 20 is 4.  We write the radicand as the product of two factors, one containing the perfect square and the largest possible even powers of the variables.  That is,
	20x^2y^3 = 4x^2y^2 \cdot 5y
Then we write the radical as a product.
	\sqrt{20x^2y^3} = \sqrt{4x^2y^2 \cdot 5y} = \sqrt{4x^2y^2}~\sqrt{5y}
Finally, we simplify the first of the two factors to find
	\sqrt{20x^2y^3}=\blert{\sqrt{4x^2y^2}}~\sqrt{5y} = \blert{2xy}~\sqrt{5y}
